Toy rotation benefits ⬇️

🌈 It decreases clutter, allows the mind to be free and have room for creativity to flourish.

🌈 It encourages independent play.

🌈Less toys to clean up.I started doing toy rotations when my son was about 6 months. I would model clean up with time and consistency he followed. 
We often underestimate how capable they are. 

🌈 Allows your child to focus more. Messes can be chaotic and unsettling. 

🌈 Saves money ( you can also look at your local buy nothing groups and donate what you don’t use ) 
A question I get alot is how many toys do I leave out and where and how do i store them .
Arrange around 9 to 12 different items on a low shelf so the child can pick a toy to focus on. Put other toys in a closet or somewhere out of reach and view.
I put the toys in bins in his closet that are all labeled, example (cars, balls, dinosaurs, puzzles ect . 

We rotate every 2/3 weeks. 

Please let me know if you have questions!!!

To the mama preparing her heart for daycare, I want you to know that it will be okay i promise you it will be. I also want you to know that it’s okay to be upset about having to return to work or have mixed feelings about it. Remember you can love your career and be upset about having to return from maternity leave. 
Know that however you are feeling is completely valid.

I know that I was EXTREMELY blessed to have 18 months of maternity leave, regardless it was still a hard transition and I still have days where I’m upset about it. ITS OK to be upset you’re human give yourself grace. 

This is the bittersweet part of parenting.
In the early days, weeks and months of parenting, you are their whole world. And the bigger they get, their world grows beyond just you—as it should. 

We are so so so so very grateful for Noah’s daycare providers they go above and beyond and most importantly they love our son. He’s so happy to go and see his little friends, he’s learning so much and as a school educator myself I know how important and good that is for him. Our son names all his friends in the drive to daycare and he’s so happy to see them and his educators. 

He still needs me, just in different ways. His world has grown and will continue to grow, but I will always be his place to land.  🤍

Children are our greatest teachers,

As parents we are here to teach them so many things but I truly believe that they are here to guide us.
They remind us to find joy in the simple moments, to slow down and appreciate everything surrounding us, that it’s okay to make mistakes and it’s beautiful to feel our emotions. 

 Children don’t need so many toys to keep them happy and busy. Allow them to be bored it helps with creativity and also developing some independent skills. 
I am always be a firm believer in less is more, less toys to clutter the house. My child does have toys he has everything he needs without overwhelming him. 

Take them outside, allow them to explore all their sense, we live in a world that’s so focused on screens that we forget to live in the now. With that being said I’m also a no bad weather day person. We dress up for the weather and enjoy it. Here in Canada we have all the extremes in one week sometimes yet we still make time for outdoor play 2/3 times a day. 

I myself being a parent of a toddler i am learning everyday how to live more mindfully and focus on the present moment. 
If your child can teach you one thing let it be to just be here in this present moment with them be silly and don’t worry about tomorrow it’s not here yet. 
This season of life is so short and so so so humbling. 🤍

What is something your child has taught you ? 

.

.

.

Things we have done to encourage our toddler to clean up. 

➡️Start a cleanup routine from early on. This can also mean you are modeling cleaning up and doing hand on hand. 
➡️ Five/ten minute reminders a visual timer helps too. 
➡️ Have a song you sing and dance to when it’s clean up time it’s a great cue for them, it also makes it fun. 
▶️Toy rotations are very beneficial because having less toys out helps with not having unnecessary clutter, each toys have their separate bins, this helps with organisation. ( check my toy rotation reel for more on this. )
Be consistent and have fun with them, toddlers love to helpful.

Be gentle with yourself you’re healing,

Lately I’ve allowed myself to dig deeper into my past traumas and let myself to feel however I have to feel about it. Society can often make us feel rushed into our journeys like there is a expiration date. 
My therapist recently told me that I need to be more gentle with myself. Since 2019 I’ve been through postpartum many times and that is a lot on someone’s body and mind. What I’ve recently also realized is that it may never be easy for me to go through pregnancy again because I was robbed from that experience after having recurrent miscarriages and I will not excuse myself from normalizing how brutally hard it is to go trough so much trauma multiple times in such short time. I also know now that postpartum with Noah was excruciatingly hard for me because I was isolated due to a pandemic but also had so much fear that something would happened to me, like I was in disbelief that I had a living baby in my house. I could go on longer on how I feel but il leave on this note.
Trauma is hard and don’t let anyone make you feel like you need to get over it or just think positive.
 

Happy weekend everyone ❤️😊 I got to squeeze in one of my best friends newborn this am and it was so good on my heart.

⬇️Sensory play benefits ⬇️

🌈 Helps to build nerve connections in the brain ( Sensory play in early childhood plays an important role in brain development because sensory stimulation is essential for sensory integration and cognitive development .)

🌈Encourages learning through exploration, and that’s a beautiful way to remind ourselves why playing is so essential to a child learning. 

🌈 Creates an opportunity for creativity, 
curiosity and problem solving. 

🌈 Helps with fine motor skills and gross motor skills 

🌈 It’s calming and supports language development. 

Here are a few material examples and most of  them are already in your house. ⬇️

▶️shaving cream
▶️ Rice/ pasta/ beans/ cereals ect 
▶️baking flour/ oatmeal 
▶️play dough
▶️cotton balls
▶️water play/ you can add ice or even food colorant 
And so much more.

This week I’ve been taking a few steps back from social media. I think for me being a working Mom I got stuck in the comparison game and felt very defeated. I had to take a step back in order to focus on what I have instead of what I don’t have. 
I consumed my own energy feeling sad that I don’t get much time to myself to recharge or weekends to myself when in reality it doesn’t belong to me what others get that I may not. We don’t always know the reality behind someone’s picture perfect life on social media. 
I know for a fact that I am lucky that I have a family that is home with me every night and that we have a roof over our head and food to eat. Sometimes it doesn’t have to be fancy and remember that most people only show the good sides of their life so it can be easy to think they all have it better.

Know that your feelings are valid and some season of life can be more challenging and it’s okay to feel overwhelmed that you don’t get time for yourself you’re a human 🤍

Let me tell you why I love chair pose (utkatasana) 
My love for chair pose only started while doing my yoga teacher training. At first I used to roll my eyes and feel annoyed when a teacher would make me hold this pose.

And it’s by getting out of my head that I was able to allow PLAYFULNESS to be a huge part of my practice.
 Not only does chair pose allow me to Invite playfulness into my practice it makes me feel POWERFUL.

“There’s nothing like a good chair pose to
make you remember just how powerful your body is, how powerful your breath is, how powerful you are. When your legs begin to tremble and you want nothing more than to give up, but you don’t…That’s power. That’s strength.”

And most importantly stay with your breath in, and instead of letting your mind wander, think about the awesome benefits of the pose.This asana is great for strengthening the thighs, ankles, calves, spine, and core . 

I hope this can remind you of how capable you are. 🤍

And if you still don’t love that pose that is also okay.
